AB  - RN Dredging have recently carried out a successful capital dredge program in Tauranga Harbour, New Zealand. The dredging involved the removal of a total of 6.9 M m3 of material and the placement of dredged material offshore of Mount Maunganui within the Port of Tauranga Deposition Site, except some 30,000 m3 of boulders, which was utilised for the creation of a submerged stone-reef near the entrance to the Harbour. The consent conditions set out limits on turbidity (both 6 hourly and 2 week running averages) at 6 key monitoring locations inside the harbour. The environmental limits were set based on an analysis of long term monitoring data, modelling and consideration of species sensitivity to elevated turbidity. These limits were used to trigger level 1 or level 2 management responses and also set absolute environmental limits that were not to be exceeded during the dredge program. Part of the Dredging Environmental Management Plan was the development of a Dredge Spill Planning Tool. This tool provided RN Dredging with a web based system that could deliver dredge spill model results for a particular user-defined dredging regime and pre-defined hydrodynamic conditions. © Australasian Coasts and Ports 2017 Conference. All rights reserved.
