UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/86000015040?origin=resultslist
AB  - During transient well testing of offshore oil and gas wells, pressure and pressure derivatives may be affected by tidal effects, resulting in periodic abnormal fluctuations that interfere with the interpretation of the model and reservoir parameters. In this paper, tidal correction is carried out using fast Fourier transform method(FFT), optimization correction method based on tidal model driver(TMD) or measured tidal data. The FFT method is to transform abnormal pressure data into the frequency domain, identify and suppress tidal anomaly characteristics; The TMD optimization correction method calculates tidal signals and optimizes their fitting with original pressure to obtain data without tidal effects; Optimization correction method based on measured tidal data requires the use of the tidal table at the test well location or the tidal table in nearby port cities, to adjust the amplitude and delay time through optimization methods to achieve tidal removal. Through research and practical well testing cases, it has been verified that the fast Fourier transform method, the optimization correction method based on tidal model driver or measured tidal data have their own characteristics when processing data from different sea areas or test conditions, we can choose one or a combination of multiple methods, which can effectively remove the influence of tides and accurately determine the radial flow characteristics and later characteristics on the pressure derivative curve. This method can effectively diagnose the characteristics of tides, identify tidal components and suppress tidal effects by integrating multiple methods during the processing of raw pressure data, avoiding the ambiguity of results and computational complexity. Compared with previous studies, the method proposed in this article has better adaptability in removing tidal effects, especially when the build-up analysis period is short, it still has a very significant processing effect. It provides an effective means for correcting abnormal pressure data containing tidal effects. Copyright 2025, International Petroleum Technology Conference.
