AB  - Structural inspections of an approach bridge to a wharf in an Australian port identified significant concrete spalling and corrosion in the prestressed spans, prompting the operator to impose a reduced load limit and restrict traffic to a single lane. While necessary for risk mitigation, these restrictions limited access for key clients and reduced the overall operational efficiency of the port. This paper presents a case study using the advanced engineering solutions to extend the life of an approach bridge at the port. A comprehensive structural assessment with the integration of the on-going structural health monitoring (SHM) systems were developed to evaluate the bridge performance. Various sensors were installed at critical locations to capture the real-time structure responses under different load conditions. Through the correlation between measured data and the advanced structural model, conservative assumptions from prior assessments could be removed. This provided the engineering justification to increase the bridge's load limit, restoring its functionality while ensuring ongoing safety. Additionally, a real-time vehicle overload detection tool was developed, enabling the operator to monitor and manage excessive loading events proactively. The integration of data monitoring and analytical modelling not only allowed the operator to make an informed decision to optimise bridge operations but also established a framework for long-term structural health monitoring. This proactive data-driven approach ensures that any future deterioration or repair works can be tracked in real time, supporting ongoing asset management strategies. This case study highlights how advanced structural assessment techniques can extend the service life of critical infrastructure, reduce unnecessary operational restrictions, and improve safety and efficiency through data-driven decision-making. © Australasian Coasts and Ports 2025.All rights reserved.
